Below is a **complete, self‑contained binding** that shows one idiomatic way to expose a C++ iterator (the one that libpcapng provides) to OCaml code.  
It contains

* a public **`.mli`** that an OCaml user will see,
* a **single C++ stub file** (`pcapng_stubs.cpp`) that can be compiled with the OCaml tool‑chain, and
* enough documentation/comments to understand how the pieces fit together.

Feel free to copy‑paste the two files into a fresh directory, adjust the `#include <libpcapng/...>` line to the real header of libpcapng, and compile with the commands at the end of the answer.

---

## 1.  The public OCaml interface – `pcapng.mli`

```ocaml
(** pcapng – OCaml bindings for libpcapng

    The library lets you open a *.pcapng* file, walk over all captured
    frames and run OCaml code for each frame – exactly the same mental
    model you get from pandas/Polars `DataFrame.iter_rows` or similar.

    The binding is deliberately low‑level (no magic “lazy streams”,
    no callbacks that survive GC) but ergonomic: you get a concrete
    OCaml record for each frame and can use ordinary higher‑order
    functions (`iter`, `fold`, `to_list`) on the collection.
*)

(** An opaque handle to an opened pcapng file. *)
type capture

(** A single captured frame.  The fields are deliberately simple so that
    the value can be created cheaply inside the C++ loop. *)
type frame = {
  timestamp : int64;   (** nanoseconds since the Unix epoch – as libpcapng reports. *)
  length    : int;     (** captured length of the packet (bytes). *)
  data      : bytes;   (** raw packet bytes, exactly [length] long. *)
}

(** Open a *.pcapng* file.  Raises [Failure] if the file cannot be opened
    or if the underlying libpcapng parser reports an error. *)
val open_file : string -> capture

(** Close a capture.  The function is idempotent – calling it twice is a
    no‑op.  The underlying C++ object is also freed automatically when
    the OCaml value becomes unreachable (via a finaliser). *)
val close : capture -> unit

(** Apply a function to every frame in the capture, in order.  The
    callback runs **inside the C++ iterator loop**, so the traversal is
    performed in C++ and only the per‑frame work is done in OCaml.  The
    callback may raise; the exception propagates outward and the
    iteration stops immediately. *)
val iter : (frame -> unit) -> capture -> unit

(** Fold over the frames.  The traversal is exactly the same as for
    [iter]; the only difference is that a value is threaded through the
    loop. *)
val fold : ('a -> frame -> 'a) -> 'a -> capture -> 'a

(** Collect all frames into a list.  This is just a convenience wrapper
    around [fold]; it is **not** the recommended way to process large
    captures because it forces the whole capture into the OCaml heap. *)
val to_list : capture -> frame list
```

